# ============================================================================
# Moral Character Ontology - BFO-Aligned Virtue and Vice Modeling
# ============================================================================
#
# Philosophical Foundation:
# - Character traits modeled as BFO dispositions (bfo:0000016)
# - Realized through concrete acts and processes (bfo:0000015)
# - Grounded in quality substrates inhering in agents (bfo:0000019)
# - Cross-worldview: applicable across all 12 worldview frameworks
#
# Primary Sources:
# - Aristotle. (350 BCE). Nicomachean Ethics. Trans. W.D. Ross. Oxford University Press.
# - Aquinas, T. (1265-74). Summa Theologica. Trans. Fathers of the English Dominican Province.
# - Hume, D. (1739-40). A Treatise of Human Nature. Book III: Of Morals.
# - Kant, I. (1785). Groundwork of the Metaphysics of Morals. Trans. Mary Gregor. Cambridge (1997).
# - MacIntyre, A. (1981). After Virtue: A Study in Moral Theory. University of Notre Dame Press.
# - Foot, P. (1978). Virtues and Vices and Other Essays in Moral Philosophy. Oxford University Press.
# - Annas, J. (2011). Intelligent Virtue. Oxford University Press.
# - Hursthouse, R. (1999). On Virtue Ethics. Oxford University Press.
#
# Contemporary Empirical Research:
# - Peterson, C., & Seligman, M. E. P. (2004). Character Strengths and Virtues: A Handbook and Classification. Oxford University Press.
# - Fleeson, W., & Jayawickreme, E. (2015). Whole Trait Theory. Journal of Research in Personality, 56, 82-92.
# - Miller, C. B. (2013). Moral Character: An Empirical Theory. Oxford University Press.
# - Doris, J. M. (2002). Lack of Character: Personality and Moral Behavior. Cambridge University Press.
# - Haidt, J. (2001). The emotional dog and its rational tail. Psychological Review, 108(4), 814-834.
# - Narvaez, D., & Lapsley, D. K. (2009). Moral identity, moral functioning, and the development of moral character. Psychology of Learning and Motivation, 50, 237-274.
#
# BFO Modeling Strategy:
# - Character traits = Dispositions (bfo:0000016) inhering in persons
# - Virtuous/vicious acts = Processes (bfo:0000015) realizing character dispositions
# - Character qualities = Quality substrates (bfo:0000019) measurable on scales
# - Character development = Extended process of disposition cultivation
#
# Integration with ValueNet:
# - Character dispositions cross-cut all Schwartz value dispositions
# - Different worldviews prioritize different character traits
# - Multi-perspectival character evaluation possible
#
# ============================================================================
